-- Anglo Platinum, Gold Fields, Sasol May Move: South African Stocks Preview
-- B y   R o n   D e r b y
-- 2010-10-14T06:18:15Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-14/anglo-platinum-cic-holdings-shares-may-move-south-african-stock-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in  South Africa .
Stock symbols are in parentheses after company names and prices
are from the last close.  South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index  breached the
30,000 level for the first time since July 2008, advancing
488.31, or 1.6 percent, to 30,267.46 at the 5 p.m. close of
trade in Johannesburg.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd.  (ANG SJ): Gold rose to a record for
a second day as the dollar slumped, stoking investor demand for
precious metals as an alternative to currencies. Shares in
AngloGold, Africa’s biggest gold miner, rose 4.90 rand, or 1.5
percent, to 324.90 rand, while  Gold Fields Ltd.  (GFI SJ), the
second-largest, gained 1.95 rand, or 1.8 percent, to 110.45
rand.  Anglo Platinum Ltd.  (AMS SJ): The world’s biggest platinum
miner said an offer by Impala Platinum Holdings Ltd. to buy the
Bafokeng Rasimone Platinum Mine venture wasn’t in the best long-
term interests of its shareholders. Shares in Anglo Platinum
gained 18.02 rand, or 2.6 percent, to 716 rand.  CIC Holdings Ltd . (CCI SJ): A Namibian company that
provides retailers with merchandising services, said that
country’s High Court would make a ruling regarding Imperial
Holdings Ltd.’s offer to acquire the company in “due course.”
Shares in CIC were unchanged at 2.85 rand.  John Daniel Holdings Ltd.  (JDH SJ): The designer and maker
of industrial containers said its full-year loss per share will
rise 31 percent, compared with previous guidance of as much as
50 percent. Shares in the company were unchanged at 11 cents.  Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ): Oil climbed for a second day in New
York after an industry-funded report showed U.S. crude supplies
fell and the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries moved
closer to seeking greater compliance with production cuts.
Shares in Sasol, the world’s biggest maker of motor fuel from
coal, climbed 3.90 rand, or 1.2 percent, to 321 rand.  Shares or American depositary receipts of the following
South African companies closed as follows:  Anglo American Plc (AAUKY US) added 5.5 percent to $22.83.
AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (AU US) rose 2.8 percent to $48.12. BHP
Billiton Ltd. (BBL US) gained 3.4 percent to $69.88. DRDGold
Ltd. (DROOY US) climbed 2.9 percent to $5.39. Gold Fields Ltd.
(GFI US) jumped 2.8 percent to $16.16. Harmony Gold Mining Co.
(HMY US) added 0.1 percent to $11.42. Impala Platinum Holdings
Co. (IMPUY US) rose 2.5 percent to $28.35. Sappi Ltd. (SPP US)
climbed 0.8 percent to $5.011. Sasol Ltd. (SSL US) fell 1.2
percent to $46.74. Telkom South Africa Ltd. (TLKGY US) gained
1.8 percent to $21.80.  To contact the reporters on this story:
